    "analysis": "Executor returned per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) summaries for the candidate socket KPIs and rabbitmq-exporter mem. All these series are constant across the incident window (25 points, unique_values_count = 1), with the first window datapoint at 2024-01-19 05:37:00 UTC. Many other KPIs and logs previously flagged as anomalies had global P95 or P5 equal to the observed constant values (including many zero-baseline KPIs), causing false-positive counts. Because the socket and mem series are constant and equal to their global thresholds, they are not necessarily true faults (they may be normal operating values). To localize a real root cause we need to find KPIs or logs that actually change during the window (non-constant) or show meaningful deviations (e.g., latency, request counts, error counts >0). Traces and detailed error_logs are empty so we must rely on metrics and logs. Next, we should scan all metric KPIs for any that vary within the incident window (unique values >1 or min != max) and check log.error_count entries that are non-zero within the incident window to identify true anomalies and possible fault start times.",
