{
    "analysis": "Executor results so far: metric.csv and log.csv are present; trace.csv and error_logs.csv are empty. Initial anomaly scan flagged many constant 'socket' and some mem series that matched their global thresholds exactly — these are constant values across the window and likely false positives. A focused variability scan (window 2024-01-19 05:34:52 — 2024-01-19 06:04:52 UTC) revealed meaningful changes for many memory (mem) time series and some diskio and CPU series. Among the allowed root-cause components (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user), the most prominent signals are: orders.mem (very large delta) and orders.cpu (large spike up to ~50), catalogue.mem (moderate delta), and user.mem (smaller delta). log.error_count shows no values >0 for any cmdb_id in-window, so logs do not show explicit errors. Because traces and error_logs are empty, we must rely on metrics analysis to determine which component and resource breached its global threshold substantially and when the fault began. Next step is to compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) for each KPI of the five candidate services using the full available series (per rules), then detect and summarize anomaly occurrences inside the incident window to identify the earliest and most severe faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For each cmdb_id in [\"carts\",\"catalogue\",\"orders\",\"payment\",\"user\"] do the following using metric.csv: (1) For every kpi_name for that cmdb_id, compute global_p95 and global_p5 using the full series (all available rows for that cmdb_id+kpi_name). (2) Filter rows to the incident window (timestamps >= '2024-01-19 05:34:52 UTC' and <= '2024-01-19 06:04:52 UTC'). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) output a single compact row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p5, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_high (count of values >= global_p95 in-window), earliest_high_timestamp_utc (or None), max_value_in_window, anomaly_count_low (count of values <= global_p5 in-window), earliest_low_timestamp_utc (or None), min_value_in_window, and severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / (global_p95 if global_p95>0 else NaN). Return only rows where anomaly_count_high>0 or anomaly_count_low>0, sorted by anomaly_count_high desc then severity_ratio desc, limit to top 20 rows." }

